# Postgres function & RLS conventions

## Every function MUST
- `set search_path = public` (or appropriate explicit schema)
- Be either `security invoker` (default, runs as caller) or explicitly `security definer` with a documented reason
- Have its EXECUTE grants reviewed: `revoke execute ... from public, anon, authenticated;` then `grant execute ... to <role>;`

## Helper functions on `profiles` (is_admin, is_staff, is_banned, current_user_role)
- `language sql stable security invoker set search_path = public`
- Profiles has public read RLS so these don't need DEFINER

## Trigger functions (counters, guards, propagation)
- `language plpgsql security invoker set search_path = public`
- Always handle null cases and use `greatest(0, x - 1)` for decrements

## RLS policy template for a new table
```sql
alter table <table> enable row level security;

create policy <table>_read on <table>
  for select using ( <readable_condition> );

create policy <table>_insert_owner on <table>
  for insert with check ( auth.uid() = user_id and not is_banned() );

create policy <table>_update_owner on <table>
  for update using ( auth.uid() = user_id );

create policy <table>_update_staff on <table>
  for update using ( is_staff() );

create policy <table>_delete_owner_or_staff on <table>
  for delete using ( auth.uid() = user_id or is_staff() );
```

## After every migration
- Run `mcp__supabase__get_advisors --type security` AND `--type performance`
- Fix every WARN and ERROR before moving on

## Forbidden in migrations
- `drop table` without explicit human "go"
- `alter table ... disable row level security`
- `create policy ... using (true)` on a write-permitted operation
- Hardcoding service role bypass
